ow D/E yet still be risky elsewhere."},{"label":"Earnings momentum","value":13.98,"unit":"% YoY","status":"ok","read":"Profit up 14% YoY \u2014 modest.","meaning":"Trailing-twelve-month net profit vs the year-ago TTM (and whether the YoY rate is rising = 'accelerating').","why_useful":"Improving, accelerating earnings tend to drive re-rating; falling profit warns of a deteriorating business.","why_it_can_fail":"TTM can be lumpy for cyclicals/one-offs; cross-check the multi-year trend on the Fundamentals tab."}]},"valuation":{"ok":true,"is_bank":false,"pe_now":20.8,"pe_percentile":83.0,"median_pe":15.5,"earnings_yield_pct":4.81,"pb":4.83,"ev_ebitda":16.26,"quality_score":96.0,"pat_cagr_5y_pct":17.1,"peg":1.22,"cheapness":{"status":"weak","read":"P/E at the 83-percentile of its 10-yr range \u2014 expensive vs its own history."},"expectations":"At 20.8\u00d7 earnings for ~17% 5-yr profit CAGR, the market is paying \u22481.22\u00d7 growth (PEG). >2 = a lot already priced in; <1 = cheap if growth holds. This PEG divides TTM P/E by TRAILING 5-year annual PAT CAGR (endpoint-to-endpoint) \u2014 a time-axis mismatch vs the textbook FORWARD-EPS PEG, and one abnormal base/terminal year distorts the CAGR. A rough trailing valuation-vs-growth gauge, not a precise forward PEG.","cyclical_caveat":null,"meaning":"P/E percentile = where today's price-to-earnings sits within the stock's own last-10-yr range (low = cheap vs its past). Paired with the Quality score and 5-yr profit growth so a cheap multiple is judged against business strength, not in isolation.","why_useful":"Cheapness only matters relative to quality and growth \u2014 a low P/E on a declining or peak-cyclical business is a trap, not a bargain.","why_it_can_fail":"P/E breaks for loss-makers / one-offs; for banks use P/B not EV/EBITDA; a multiple cheap vs history can stay cheap if the business has structurally de-rated."},"ownership":{"ok":true,"na":null,"holders":{"Promoter":{"periods":["Mar 2019","Jun 2019","Sep 2019"